WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:44.080 --> 00:46.367
<i>We were a real business.</i>

00:46.520 --> 00:48.921
<i>That's what
you got to understand.</i>

00:51.240 --> 00:53.402
<i>We were goddamn industry...</i>

00:54.840 --> 00:57.684
<i>the kind that's the backbone
of this country.</i>

00:59.640 --> 01:00.766
Don't take my word for it.

01:00.880 --> 01:02.456
Go in the parking lot
and look on the license

01:02.480 --> 01:04.801
of that brand-new
Mercedes 450 of yours.

01:06.040 --> 01:08.566
Hey. Are you seeing this?

01:08.680 --> 01:10.011
That's Furnace Creek.

01:10.120 --> 01:11.640
This, uh, picture's
over 100 years old.

01:11.680 --> 01:12.966
Hmm.

01:13.080 --> 01:14.936
And you see this
handsome devil right here?

01:14.960 --> 01:16.564
Uh-huh.

01:16.720 --> 01:18.245
He's a Wells.

01:18.360 --> 01:22.160
Okay, so, um, I know
you're a mining company,

01:22.280 --> 01:25.090
- Mm-hmm.
- But I pictured...

01:25.200 --> 01:26.880
Well, I don't know
what I pictured exactly.

01:26.920 --> 01:28.604
I guess little... little carts

01:28.720 --> 01:30.848
going down little...
little train tracks.

01:30.960 --> 01:32.769
- Right. -I mean, what is it
that you do here?

01:32.880 --> 01:34.723
Wh-what we do
is we look for the metals

01:34.840 --> 01:36.046
and the minerals, all right?

01:36.160 --> 01:37.924
There's exploration over there,

01:38.040 --> 01:41.283
there's engineering
and there's production, right?

01:41.400 --> 01:43.767
We're prospectors.

01:44.880 --> 01:46.530
<i>Not yet'?</i>

01:46.640 --> 01:48.051
- Okay, how about this?
- Yeah...

01:48.160 --> 01:51.687
Um... so let's say that this...

01:51.840 --> 01:53.080
is the Earth.

01:53.200 --> 01:54.200
My handbag?

01:54.240 --> 01:55.924
Your handbag is Mother Earth

01:56.040 --> 01:57.610
with all of her
deep-filled mysteries

01:57.760 --> 01:59.936
and goodies on the inside that
she does not want to give up.

01:59.960 --> 02:01.689
Me, I'm man,

02:01.800 --> 02:03.882
and I'm damn curious about
what she's got inside.

02:04.000 --> 02:07.049
So, I send down what's
called an exploratory drill.

02:07.160 --> 02:10.050
I go down inside and dig around,

02:10.160 --> 02:11.730
come across something.

02:11.840 --> 02:14.207
I pull it out. It's nickel.

02:14.360 --> 02:17.762
Now, nickel's actually
75% copper and 25% nickel,

02:17.880 --> 02:19.176
but there's a whole lot
of nickel in the world,

02:19.200 --> 02:21.646
and the world needs nickels.

02:21.760 --> 02:23.842
I'm back down there getting
my second core sample,

02:23.960 --> 02:26.281
and I happen to pull up, say...

02:26.400 --> 02:27.890
silver.

02:28.040 --> 02:29.696
Now, the thing is, when you
find a little bit of this,

02:29.720 --> 02:31.416
that means there could be
a whole hell of a lot of it.

02:31.440 --> 02:32.965
So we start raising money.

02:33.080 --> 02:35.481
We raise enough money
to open a mine

02:35.600 --> 02:37.284
like the one in that picture
right here.

02:37.400 --> 02:40.563
Then...

02:40.720 --> 02:42.768
we dig it all up.

02:42.880 --> 02:47.169
Now, sometimes...
Not that often, but sometimes...

02:47.280 --> 02:50.284
The prospecting gods are having
a party at the Pearly Gates,

02:50.440 --> 02:53.330
and we get real, real,
really lucky.

02:53.480 --> 02:55.164
And we dig down in there,

02:55.320 --> 02:58.164
then we find
a little metal called...

02:58.320 --> 03:00.322
gold.

03:04.320 --> 03:06.368
- Yes.
- Kenny.

03:06.480 --> 03:07.925
You like it?

03:08.080 --> 03:09.764
I love you.

03:13.360 --> 03:16.170
I love you.

03:16.280 --> 03:18.169
Old man wants to see you.

03:19.680 --> 03:21.364
Afternoon, Marianne.

03:21.480 --> 03:23.336
Hey, Pop.
Heard you want to see me.

03:23.360 --> 03:24.566
Yeah, Kenny.

03:24.720 --> 03:27.121
Get your ass in here, would you?

03:27.240 --> 03:28.605
Would you, uh, run through this

03:28.720 --> 03:30.609
Pershing County strategy
again for me?

03:30.720 --> 03:32.882
Right, um...

03:33.000 --> 03:35.367
It's about this southern part
of this Newmont property,

03:35.480 --> 03:36.766
right here.

03:36.880 --> 03:39.201
Now, Newmont just started
drilling 140 meters

03:39.360 --> 03:41.096
and they're finding
a whole lot of magnesite.

03:41.120 --> 03:43.885
If you remember, we still own
the option on Relief Canyon,

03:44.000 --> 03:46.048
which is next door.
We're not finding squat, why?

03:46.200 --> 03:47.770
We're not drilling deep enough.

03:47.880 --> 03:49.609
Let's get back in there.
Drill deeper.

03:49.720 --> 03:52.724
Go to 140 if we need to,
and we got a damn good chance

03:52.840 --> 03:54.683
of getting Relief
back in production.

03:54.800 --> 03:56.689
What about Jerritt Canyon?

03:56.800 --> 03:58.643
Well, that's your baby.

03:58.800 --> 04:01.041
You know a hell of a lot
more about it than I do.

04:01.160 --> 04:02.764
But the assays look promising.

04:02.880 --> 04:04.484
Could be fucking huge.

04:09.480 --> 04:11.369
I want you to run point on this.

04:11.520 --> 04:13.682
All in.

04:13.800 --> 04:15.882
Scale it up.

04:16.000 --> 04:17.843
Make it yours.

04:17.959 --> 04:20.440
Yes, sir.

04:24.000 --> 04:25.047
Clive Coleman's on board.

04:25.200 --> 04:26.725
Those boys will ride with you.

04:34.200 --> 04:36.441
God, we work hard
in this business.

04:36.560 --> 04:38.403
Sometimes for nothing.

04:40.360 --> 04:42.567
I wake up every morning.
I tell myself,

04:42.680 --> 04:45.411
"I don't have to do this.

04:45.520 --> 04:47.363
I get to do this."

04:49.840 --> 04:53.401
And then it's just blue skies.

05:02.280 --> 05:05.045
Blue skies, baby.

05:08.920 --> 05:11.241
<i>My old man...</i>

05:11.360 --> 05:13.328
a <i>legend.</i>

05:14.760 --> 05:18.242
<i>That was the last time
I saw him alive.</i>

05:51.680 --> 05:53.250
A little eye-opener, Kenny?

05:53.360 --> 05:55.601
God bless you, Roy.

05:55.720 --> 05:58.644
Here we are.

05:58.760 --> 06:01.127
- Boys, to the mother lode.
- Mother lode.

06:01.240 --> 06:03.242
Today be the day.

06:03.360 --> 06:05.328
<i>The geological reports on this</i>

06:05.440 --> 06:06.487
are highly encouraging.

06:06.600 --> 06:09.080
We are taking a very
aggressive approach.

06:09.200 --> 06:10.200
Prospectus?
Of course.

06:10.280 --> 06:12.056
I can have my secretary
send you one right out.

06:12.080 --> 06:14.242
But I got to tell you,
this offering,

06:14.360 --> 06:16.044
it's already over-subscribed.

06:16.160 --> 06:18.096
You know, we can always try
and get you in on the next one.

06:18.120 --> 06:20.726
No, no.
Yea, I understand.

06:21.880 --> 06:23.086
Shit.

06:23.200 --> 06:25.965
Watching the time?
It's 11:15, Kenny.

06:26.080 --> 06:28.447
Oh, Christ.

06:30.360 --> 06:32.249
Where would I be without you?

06:39.560 --> 06:41.608
Mr. Wells?

06:41.720 --> 06:43.449
- Yes.
- Lloyd Stanton.

06:43.560 --> 06:45.244
- Hello, Lloyd. Kenny Wells.
- Hi.

06:45.360 --> 06:46.816
This is my colleague,
Henry Andrews.

06:46.840 --> 06:47.960
- Pleased to meet you.
- Hey.

06:48.000 --> 06:50.241
- Come on back.
- Absolutely.

06:50.360 --> 06:52.727
Thank you.

06:56.000 --> 06:58.970
So, what can we do for ya?

06:59.080 --> 07:00.969
Well, why don't we wait
for Clive?

07:01.080 --> 07:03.321
Oh, uh, Mr. Coleman
got tied up in a meeting.

07:03.480 --> 07:04.845
No offense, boys,

07:04.960 --> 07:07.088
but I'm supposed to be meeting
with Clive.

07:07.200 --> 07:09.009
None taken, but if you were
supposed to be

07:09.120 --> 07:11.202
meeting with Clive, you
would be meeting with Clive.

07:14.240 --> 07:16.129
All right.
Here is what we have.

07:16.240 --> 07:19.244
We are developing some
very exciting properties

07:19.360 --> 07:22.125
that are spot-on
for your investor profile.

07:22.240 --> 07:26.962
Low buy-in
with a sizable upside.

07:27.080 --> 07:28.496
- Mm-hmm.
- And the beautiful part is

07:28.520 --> 07:32.241
they are all only 12 to 18
months and cash positive.

07:32.360 --> 07:33.566
- Manitoba?
- Yeah.

07:33.720 --> 07:36.485
We picked up an option
on a skip claim at an auction.

07:36.640 --> 07:38.165
Right, but it's
a 90-day option.

07:38.280 --> 07:39.611
Yes, the window is narrow,

07:39.720 --> 07:41.096
but if you have a look
at the Jerritt,

07:41.120 --> 07:42.496
you'll see a very promising
shale formation

07:42.520 --> 07:44.841
that hasn't been tapped yet.

07:47.640 --> 07:49.802
Mr. Wells,
Washoe has a practical value

07:49.920 --> 07:51.126
hovering just above zero.

07:51.280 --> 07:53.044
Your debt load is untenable,

07:53.200 --> 07:55.965
and you bring us, uh, raw land
with no infrastructure,

07:56.120 --> 07:58.361
no fungible assets.
I mean,

07:58.480 --> 08:00.176
you can't possibly expect us
to underwrite this.

08:00.200 --> 08:02.441
Yeah. I'm talking about
a small offering here.

08:02.560 --> 08:04.160
As I said in the beginning,
a low buy-in.

08:04.200 --> 08:06.362
Now, if you'll take
a second look at the Jerritt,

08:06.480 --> 08:08.528
you will see what I see.

08:08.640 --> 08:11.041
And that's money.

08:13.160 --> 08:15.049
Not our money.

08:42.280 --> 08:43.804
<i>See, the... the thing is</i>

08:43.960 --> 08:46.167
<i>that the whole economy
had turned,</i>

08:46.280 --> 08:48.601
<i>particularly for commodities.</i>

08:51.240 --> 08:52.924
<i>Close of the day,</i>

08:53.040 --> 08:55.407
<i>Washoe was trading
at four cents a share</i>

08:55.520 --> 08:57.682
<i>if it was trading at all.</i>

08:57.800 --> 08:59.928
Washoe Mining. There's this
great little land lease.

09:00.040 --> 09:03.408
'Cause this is a once
in a lifetime opportunity.

09:03.560 --> 09:05.403
Right. Washoe. Washoe Mining.

09:05.560 --> 09:08.006
You know, carrying the...
carrying on the business.

09:08.120 --> 09:10.566
You know, there's still
minerals out there.

09:10.680 --> 09:11.936
We just got to find them, right?

09:11.960 --> 09:13.016
Yeah, all right, all right.

09:13.040 --> 09:14.520
Thank... thank you
for your time. Bye.

09:17.400 --> 09:18.606
I could...

09:18.720 --> 09:20.245
<i>12 to 18 months...</i>

09:20.360 --> 09:22.283
cash positive.

09:22.400 --> 09:24.801
A deal...

09:24.920 --> 09:26.046
Goddamn, I am calling you.

09:26.160 --> 09:27.650
Fuck whatever time it is.

09:29.800 --> 09:32.690
<i>Washoe Mining,</i>

09:32.840 --> 09:34.604
<i>the company that my grandfather</i>

09:34.760 --> 09:37.969
<i>literally scratched out of
the side of a Nevada mountain,</i>

09:38.080 --> 09:42.165
<i>the company that my father
made into a real player,</i>

09:42.280 --> 09:45.329
<i>was almost gone.</i>

09:45.440 --> 09:47.807
<i>Almost.</i>

09:51.880 --> 09:55.168
<i>I'd already, uh, lost my house,</i>

09:55.320 --> 09:58.403
<i>and I was, uh...
I was living with Kay.</i>

09:58.520 --> 10:02.047
<i>And, uh, we-we were about
to lose that, too.</i>

10:12.720 --> 10:15.690
<i>I had a half gallon
of Seagram's in me.</i>

10:15.840 --> 10:18.446
<i>Shit, most people would have
been dead, but not me. No.</i>

10:20.440 --> 10:22.329
<i>Instead...</i>

10:22.440 --> 10:24.966
<i>I had a dream.</i>

10:28.480 --> 10:31.450
<i>I mean, I mean,
I mean, literally, I...</i>

10:31.560 --> 10:34.404
<i>I had a dream.</i>

10:40.760 --> 10:44.207
<i>Indonesia.</i>

10:44.320 --> 10:46.129
<i>Gold.</i>

10:49.000 --> 10:52.607
<i>Now, I'd been to Indonesia
five or six years earlier.</i>

10:52.720 --> 10:54.563
<i>I still had a little money
in my pocket.</i>

10:54.680 --> 10:56.330
<i>You know, Indonesia was booming,</i>

10:56.440 --> 10:58.807
<i>and I was looking
for a way to get in.</i>

11:03.200 --> 11:04.884
<i>Back then, if you wanted</i>

11:05.000 --> 11:06.576
<i>to put a hole in the ground
in Indonesia,</i>

11:06.600 --> 11:09.729
<i>you wanted Mike Acosta
telling you where to dig.</i>

11:09.840 --> 11:12.207
<i>He's what they called
a River Walker.</i>

11:12.320 --> 11:14.004
<i>Yeah, a real hands-on
geologist.</i>

11:14.120 --> 11:15.120
<i>The real deal.</i>

11:17.040 --> 11:18.326
<i>Oxford College, MIT.</i>

11:18.440 --> 11:19.726
<i>His mom was Venezuelan.</i>

11:19.840 --> 11:22.081
<i>His dad was English.</i>

11:24.160 --> 11:25.480
<i>Now, you see,
he'd just discovered</i>

11:25.560 --> 11:28.166
<i>the largest copper strike
in Southeast Asia,</i>

11:28.280 --> 11:32.524
<i>and everybody wanted
a piece of him, including me.</i>

11:32.640 --> 11:35.325
You got the Nazca Plate,
the Pacific Plate.

11:35.440 --> 11:37.727
Juan de Fuca,
North American, South American.

11:37.880 --> 11:39.609
Aleutian, Marianas, Tonga.

11:39.760 --> 11:42.491
The plates rubbing
and grinding up on each other.

11:42.600 --> 11:44.284
Six trillion kilobytes
of pressure.

11:44.400 --> 11:48.166
10,000 degrees Celsius
kicking up geothermic hot spots

11:48.280 --> 11:50.169
all along the Pacific rim.

11:50.280 --> 11:54.410
<i>He called it the, uh,
the Ring of Fire theory.</i>

11:54.520 --> 11:56.522
<i>And he definitely had
everyone's attention.</i>

11:56.640 --> 11:59.166
That's how I found the copper.

11:59.320 --> 12:02.608
And that's why
I'll find the gold.

12:17.520 --> 12:19.010
You're up early.

12:19.120 --> 12:20.770
Hey.-

12:23.000 --> 12:24.570
You want to talk
about yesterday.

12:24.720 --> 12:27.849
No. I gotta go right now, babe.
I've gotta plan. Gotta plan.

12:27.960 --> 12:30.201
- Oh, wait, Kenny, Kenny, listen.
- Hmm?

12:30.320 --> 12:32.209
Carl had an idea.

12:32.320 --> 12:34.607
- American Home Carl?
- Uh-huh.

12:34.720 --> 12:37.291
He said he could, uh,
get you on for a while,

12:37.440 --> 12:39.136
- if you wanted.
- Right, right, right, right.

12:39.160 --> 12:41.925
Yeah, I don't think that's
going to be necessary, babe.

12:42.040 --> 12:43.690
Yeah, but it'd just be temporary

12:43.800 --> 12:45.404
till the market turns.

12:45.520 --> 12:48.649
We could fool around
in the warehouse.

12:48.760 --> 12:50.125
You know, I tell you...

12:51.600 --> 12:53.216
When I get done with this trip,
all right?

12:53.240 --> 12:54.520
Shouldn't take more than a week.

12:54.560 --> 12:56.000
- All right.
- What? Where you going?

12:56.080 --> 12:58.401
- If it doesn't work out,
I'll give Carl a call. -Baby...

12:58.520 --> 13:00.216
- I'll call you from the airport.
- Wait. Wait, wait.

13:00.240 --> 13:01.571
Kenny!

13:01.680 --> 13:05.082
<i>It was like
I was being called, you know?</i>

13:06.840 --> 13:09.241
<i>It was the gold calling.</i>

13:09.360 --> 13:11.124
<i>That may sound crazy to you,</i>

13:11.240 --> 13:13.163
<i>but if you...
if you knew that feeling,</i>

13:13.280 --> 13:15.408
well, you'd know.

13:49.320 --> 13:51.209
<i>Kenny Wells.
I'm down here in the, uh,</i>

13:51.320 --> 13:52.760
the lobby of the, uh,
Jakarta Palace.

13:52.840 --> 13:54.444
Uh... Yeah, listen,

13:54.600 --> 13:56.090
<i>we must've got
the times mixed up.</i>

13:56.200 --> 13:58.123
<i>Um... Let me know.
I'm down here.</i>

13:58.240 --> 14:01.369
<i>I'm in the brown suit,
I'm on the green couch.</i>

14:01.480 --> 14:02.720
I'm the good-looking guy, okay?

14:02.800 --> 14:04.256
All right.
We'll make it happen, Fuca.

14:04.280 --> 14:05.486
All right.

14:10.360 --> 14:11.600
Wells?

14:11.720 --> 14:13.529
Mike.

14:16.480 --> 14:18.881
Good to see you again.

14:19.040 --> 14:22.249
I know a local place,
a bit more color.

14:22.360 --> 14:24.488
What, they're not pouring here?

14:25.800 --> 14:27.802
Good.

14:27.920 --> 14:30.810
So,

14:30.920 --> 14:33.526
what are we talking about
here, Wells?

14:35.440 --> 14:37.010
Ring of Fire, Mike.

14:37.120 --> 14:38.610
Ring of Fire.

14:38.720 --> 14:41.690
You're playing my greatest hits.

14:41.800 --> 14:44.041
Fire's gone out of that one.

14:44.160 --> 14:45.924
Well, what are you
talking about?

14:46.040 --> 14:49.886
It's the opinion of my
fellow esteemed geologists,

14:50.000 --> 14:52.446
that the whole thing...
I'm quoting here...

14:52.560 --> 14:54.608
Is a crock of shit.

14:54.720 --> 14:56.768
Well, what the hell, you know?

14:56.880 --> 14:58.644
You called it wrong.

14:59.840 --> 15:01.729
What are you going to do?

15:01.840 --> 15:04.525
There's no right or wrong
in this business.

15:04.640 --> 15:06.927
There's only hits and misses.

15:07.040 --> 15:09.646
There's gold here.

15:15.760 --> 15:18.366
I'm glad you said that, Mike.

15:18.520 --> 15:20.807
I truly am, 'cause I...

15:22.440 --> 15:24.010
believe you.

15:24.120 --> 15:26.407
I hate to dash your hopes,
but don't you think

15:26.520 --> 15:28.576
others have come along
before you with the same thought

15:28.600 --> 15:32.525
and, from the looks of it,
deeper pockets?

15:32.640 --> 15:35.325
Ring of Fire is real, Mike.

15:35.440 --> 15:36.805
I knew it
the first time I heard.

15:36.920 --> 15:38.604
It struck me like
a fucking lightning bolt,

15:38.720 --> 15:40.324
and I never forgot it.

15:40.440 --> 15:42.488
Go ahead, laugh.
I get that all the time.

15:42.600 --> 15:45.080
But hear this.

15:45.200 --> 15:47.407
I don't just believe.

15:47.520 --> 15:48.965
I know.

15:49.080 --> 15:51.162
- No, you don't.
- I've seen it.

15:51.280 --> 15:54.409
You don't understand.

15:54.520 --> 15:57.729
- No one will back me.
- I will.

15:57.840 --> 15:59.968
You tell me where
you want to dig, Mikey,

16:00.080 --> 16:02.970
and I'll make goddamn sure
the bills are paid.

16:04.240 --> 16:05.844
No offense, Wells, but...

16:05.960 --> 16:08.691
you look like you had to rob
someone just to get here, man.

16:08.800 --> 16:11.644
You know nothing about me.

16:11.760 --> 16:13.967
You know it's still out there.

16:15.200 --> 16:17.282
I know that.

16:17.400 --> 16:20.290
I can see it in your eyes.
You still believe.

16:22.160 --> 16:25.482
I get it, and I was born on
the side of the mountain, too.

16:25.600 --> 16:27.216
My-my father scratched
everything he ever owned

16:27.240 --> 16:28.605
out of a fucking rock.
All right?

16:28.720 --> 16:29.976
Died with dirt
under his fingernails,

16:30.000 --> 16:31.684
and I intend to do the same.

16:31.840 --> 16:33.569
This business...

16:33.720 --> 16:35.324
wrote me off years ago.

16:35.440 --> 16:36.736
All right, maybe you're
not running the hottest

16:36.760 --> 16:37.976
in your career right now either,

16:38.000 --> 16:39.206
so let's prove them wrong.

16:39.320 --> 16:40.481
You and me.

16:40.640 --> 16:41.856
Let's prove them all
fucking wrong.

16:41.880 --> 16:43.166
And you know why?

16:44.360 --> 16:46.681
You do know why,
because the Ring of Fire

16:46.800 --> 16:49.963
is right, Mike.
You called it.

16:50.080 --> 16:52.811
You just haven't found it yet.

16:54.840 --> 16:57.047
Tell me I'm crazy.

16:57.200 --> 16:59.567
I'll be on the next plane.

17:04.480 --> 17:06.608
You're crazy.

17:16.319 --> 17:17.810
You have a hat, Wells?

17:20.960 --> 17:23.361
Yeah, I got a hat.

17:23.520 --> 17:24.931
Why, we going somewhere?

17:25.040 --> 17:27.691
<i>Up river.</i>

17:27.800 --> 17:30.201
<i>What river is that, Mike?</i>

17:30.360 --> 17:32.010
You're late.

17:32.120 --> 17:33.929
<i>The only one that matters.</i>

17:59.000 --> 18:00.889
The Dayak have been
panning this river

18:01.000 --> 18:03.480
for over 5,000 years.

18:03.640 --> 18:06.041
That's how it got its name,

18:06.160 --> 18:08.208
Daya Kensana.

18:08.320 --> 18:09.924
What's it mean?

18:10.040 --> 18:11.804
"Daya" means "upstream."

18:12.800 --> 18:14.802
"Kensana" means "gold."

18:15.880 --> 18:18.281
You got to be shitting me.

18:38.440 --> 18:39.965
Wells.

18:40.080 --> 18:41.241
Wells.

18:41.360 --> 18:42.930
We're here.

18:43.040 --> 18:46.249
So, listen, the Dayak
are warrior people,

18:46.360 --> 18:48.886
probably best known for Dayak,

18:49.000 --> 18:50.604
headhunting.

18:50.720 --> 18:53.166
But it doesn't happen much
anymore.

18:53.280 --> 18:55.169
They might be thinking
we're some traders

18:55.320 --> 18:56.446
or someone's mother-in-law.

19:16.720 --> 19:17.801
How long?

19:19.080 --> 19:21.447
This jungle
will... will test you.

19:22.800 --> 19:26.850
It will hold you up, weigh you,

19:26.960 --> 19:28.724
and decide your worth
within an ounce.

19:28.840 --> 19:30.569
Do you always talk
like this, Mike?

19:30.680 --> 19:33.206
Like a book on tape?

19:33.320 --> 19:35.641
I suppose I do.

19:37.760 --> 19:40.525
Where are we going?

19:40.640 --> 19:42.324
Up.

19:55.080 --> 19:57.287
Take a look.

20:06.720 --> 20:08.324
Oh, my God.

20:12.920 --> 20:14.888
It's my dream.

20:15.000 --> 20:16.889
There have been
a few folks up here

20:17.000 --> 20:18.809
tapping over the years,

20:18.920 --> 20:21.764
but have all focused on the
foothills far to the south.

20:21.880 --> 20:25.248
But what interests me
is the other way.

20:25.360 --> 20:27.408
That small depression,

20:27.520 --> 20:31.241
like a giant left a footprint
walking away.

20:31.360 --> 20:33.886
Something happened there, Wells.

20:34.040 --> 20:37.886
Something hot and angry.

20:38.000 --> 20:40.606
That's where we'll find
the tasty bits.

20:41.960 --> 20:43.485
My dream...

20:48.320 --> 20:50.288
is out there.

20:50.400 --> 20:52.528
Damn right it is.

20:55.520 --> 20:57.568
<i>Look, if it's the big boys</i>

20:57.680 --> 20:59.440
<i>that you're thinking about
investing in us...</i>

20:59.520 --> 21:01.124
<i>You know, the Harvard endowment</i>

21:01.280 --> 21:03.726
<i>or some...
some pension fund, right?...</i>

21:03.840 --> 21:06.320
I am not your guy.

21:06.440 --> 21:08.966
But the little guys, right,

21:09.120 --> 21:10.724
guys that you don't even
know about,

21:10.840 --> 21:12.524
the, uh, the hustlers,
the scrappers,

21:12.640 --> 21:14.449
the make-it-happen
motherfuckers,

21:14.560 --> 21:16.483
those are my guys.

21:17.840 --> 21:20.491
How much do we need?

21:20.600 --> 21:24.321
Seven. Seven-fifty to start.

21:24.440 --> 21:26.841
Okay.

21:27.800 --> 21:30.371
How much do we need?

21:30.480 --> 21:32.562
It isn't just a lease.

21:32.680 --> 21:34.364
We're in Indonesia.

21:34.520 --> 21:38.684
That means getting a permit
and lining pockets.

21:38.800 --> 21:40.609
Equipment.
You don't just do this

21:40.720 --> 21:42.210
with a couple of shovels
and a pickax.

21:42.360 --> 21:43.930
I'll get the money.

21:44.040 --> 21:45.769
Whatever it takes.

21:55.880 --> 21:58.281
- What's that?
- It's a contract.

21:58.400 --> 21:59.890
Read it.

22:00.000 --> 22:01.968
Sign it.

22:17.000 --> 22:18.968
Keep it.

22:20.560 --> 22:23.211
<i>I could feel it in my bones.</i>

22:23.360 --> 22:26.091
<i>I was selling something
that I believed in.</i>

22:29.360 --> 22:30.646
20-K minimum buy-in, right,

22:30.760 --> 22:32.616
and the shares are fucking
flying off the shelf.

22:32.640 --> 22:33.920
I mean, no risk, no gain, right?

22:33.960 --> 22:36.440
No, 'cause it's coming in
right now.

22:36.560 --> 22:38.289
No, Acosta. Michael Acosta.

22:38.400 --> 22:39.616
It's the largest
copper strike in history,

22:39.640 --> 22:41.085
and that's the guy that we got.

22:41.200 --> 22:42.976
Kay, get those shoes shined
for dancing, baby.

22:43.000 --> 22:44.216
<i>We don't even have
the exploration permits.</i>

22:44.240 --> 22:46.607
What are they selling?

22:46.760 --> 22:48.250
What are we selling?

22:50.200 --> 22:52.009
Mikey, we're selling the story.

22:52.120 --> 22:54.930
And right now, the story is you.

22:55.040 --> 22:57.280
Speaking of which, what the fuck
are you doing right now?

22:57.360 --> 22:59.931
I'm down in Kupang City
looking at coring equipment.

23:00.040 --> 23:02.930
Acosta's in Kupang City
looking at coring equipment.

23:03.040 --> 23:04.610
He's in Kupang City as we speak.

23:04.720 --> 23:06.563
It-it's a fucking...

23:06.680 --> 23:08.416
Kupang City. We're getting
the coring equipment...

23:08.440 --> 23:10.124
You're magic, Mike.
You're fucking magic.

23:21.680 --> 23:22.727
You there, Mike?

23:24.200 --> 23:26.248
Two hundred
and sixty-seven thousand

23:26.360 --> 23:28.408
four hundred and thirty-four...

23:28.520 --> 23:30.284
<i>dollars.</i>

23:30.400 --> 23:32.846
That's not exactly the number
I had in mind, Wells.

23:32.960 --> 23:35.167
Well, look, I may be able
to borrow a little bit

23:35.280 --> 23:37.089
against it, but, you know...

23:37.200 --> 23:38.929
No, you know what?
Truth, Mike?

23:39.040 --> 23:40.326
Th-that's it for now.

23:40.480 --> 23:43.245
Th-that's it.
Can you make it work? Hmm?

23:44.960 --> 23:46.166
I can make anything work.

23:46.280 --> 23:49.045
You work out of a bar, Wells?

23:50.320 --> 23:52.527
Keeping a lid on expenses, Mike.

23:52.640 --> 23:54.802
Making the dollar holler.

23:56.920 --> 23:58.490
We're in!

24:55.560 --> 24:57.961
Record player. That's classy.

24:58.080 --> 24:59.684
Am I paying for that, Mikey?

24:59.800 --> 25:01.529
Six-man crews,

25:01.640 --> 25:04.803
12-hour shifts
around the clock.

25:04.920 --> 25:07.571
Tomorrow we'll start looking
at our core samples.

25:07.680 --> 25:09.170
Then we'll send
the most promising

25:09.280 --> 25:11.760
down river to the assay lab.

25:11.880 --> 25:13.564
The mother lode, Mike.

25:15.040 --> 25:17.008
You're out there, baby.

26:00.160 --> 26:03.448
The man that invented
the hamburger was smart, Mike.

26:03.560 --> 26:06.086
The man who invented
the cheeseburger,

26:06.200 --> 26:07.850
now, that's the genius.

26:08.000 --> 26:10.731
Don't ask where
the meat came from. Hmm?

26:10.880 --> 26:14.930
Have you ever read
Christopher Columbus' journals?

26:15.040 --> 26:16.849
Of course not.

26:16.960 --> 26:19.611
In his petition
to the queen of Spain,

26:19.760 --> 26:21.489
he promised the conversion

26:21.640 --> 26:26.407
to her holy faith
of a great number of peoples.

26:26.560 --> 26:31.441
And he went on
and mentioned God 26 times.

26:31.560 --> 26:35.042
Gold, on the other hand,

26:35.160 --> 26:39.210
he mentioned 114 times.

26:39.320 --> 26:40.845
Smart dago.

26:40.960 --> 26:43.042
I've been wanting
to ask you something, Wells.

26:43.200 --> 26:44.690
Fire away, Mike.

26:44.800 --> 26:47.121
What's the meaning of
the tattoo on your arm?

26:47.240 --> 26:48.890
Oh, it's a bird.

26:50.440 --> 26:54.206
It's from a poem I read
when I was a kid.

26:54.320 --> 26:56.482
Bird with no feet...

26:56.600 --> 26:58.443
sleeps in the wind.

27:12.440 --> 27:14.169
Assay!

27:14.280 --> 27:16.362
Assay! Assay!

27:36.080 --> 27:37.730
Mike, Mike!

27:37.880 --> 27:40.884
Hey. These things, they look
worse every time we get one.

27:41.000 --> 27:42.736
Do you remember what
I told you about patience?

27:42.760 --> 27:44.696
Yeah, you-you remember
what I told you about money?

27:44.720 --> 27:45.881
- Yeah.
- Huh?

27:46.000 --> 27:47.816
- You said that it wasn't a problem.
- Well, it...

27:47.840 --> 27:49.410
it's a fucking problem now!

28:37.360 --> 28:38.441
Hey!

28:41.280 --> 28:42.281
Hey!

28:42.400 --> 28:43.686
Hey...

28:43.800 --> 28:44.687
Hey, wait!

28:44.800 --> 28:45.801
Stay! Stay! Stay! Stay!

28:49.440 --> 28:50.440
Hey!

28:50.480 --> 28:51.845
Stay...

28:53.840 --> 28:55.729
Hey! Stay-

28:55.840 --> 28:57.126
Stay!

29:05.560 --> 29:07.562
<i>On top of everything else,</i>

29:07.720 --> 29:11.008
<i>I... I got a bad case
of malaria,</i>

29:11.120 --> 29:13.566
<i>which kills like something
like a million people a year,</i>

29:13.680 --> 29:15.091
<i>something like that.</i>

29:15.200 --> 29:18.283
<i>Suddenly, I was on the list.</i>

29:27.320 --> 29:29.800
Maybe... maybe we were
pushing them too hard.

29:29.920 --> 29:32.924
Maybe we should just
take it easy, you know?

29:33.080 --> 29:34.525
Cut them in.

29:34.640 --> 29:37.007
You know,
give them some ownership.

29:37.120 --> 29:41.489
Maybe they'll come back,
you know?

29:41.600 --> 29:43.602
Let them know that they
got something at the end,

29:43.760 --> 29:45.444
you know, when it all works out.

29:48.800 --> 29:51.121
Give them a piece of the pie,
you know?

29:51.240 --> 29:52.321
Get up.

29:52.440 --> 29:54.681
Come on, get up.

29:59.240 --> 30:00.730
I'm freezing, Mike.

30:14.480 --> 30:16.721
Don't let me die
and have nothing, okay?

30:19.560 --> 30:21.130
Get some rest now.

31:54.920 --> 31:56.604
I'm pulling the plug.

31:59.600 --> 32:01.329
No.

32:02.640 --> 32:04.290
No, no, no, no, no.

32:04.440 --> 32:06.283
Don't pull the plug, Mike.

32:07.800 --> 32:10.087
No, no.
You can't do that, Mikey.

32:10.200 --> 32:13.204
Let's get you
out of here, Wells.

32:13.320 --> 32:15.084
What's the plan, Mikey?

32:15.240 --> 32:17.004
Hmm?

32:17.160 --> 32:20.767
Now, I know you got
a plan, Mike, hmm?

32:20.880 --> 32:23.281
I know you got a plan.

32:25.480 --> 32:27.244
What's the plan, hmm?

32:29.480 --> 32:30.480
What's the plan?

32:33.680 --> 32:36.206
They need clean water.

32:36.320 --> 32:37.731
If we get filter systems
up here,

32:37.840 --> 32:39.968
I think they might come back.

32:56.000 --> 32:59.800
I got about $1,800
on this Visa right there.

32:59.920 --> 33:02.924
Close to 500
on this Diner's Club.

33:09.320 --> 33:11.527
Use it all, hmm?

33:11.640 --> 33:13.961
Use it all, Mikey.

33:47.360 --> 33:49.966
<i>Damned if he didn't go</i>

33:50.080 --> 33:51.605
<i>to every single place</i>

33:51.720 --> 33:54.087
<i>that every one
of our workers lived.</i>

33:54.200 --> 33:56.407
<i>Streams that had no name.</i>

33:56.520 --> 33:59.444
<i>All feeding
the great Kensana River.</i>

34:00.920 --> 34:03.161
Whoa!

34:13.560 --> 34:14.846
But you know what?

34:14.960 --> 34:16.643
<i>The workers came back.</i>

34:18.400 --> 34:22.688
<i>I spent the next few weeks
in a malarial haze.</i>

34:22.800 --> 34:24.882
<i>Should've been dead.</i>

34:25.040 --> 34:28.408
<i>But Mike kept it all going.</i>

35:07.320 --> 35:09.448
What day is it?

35:10.920 --> 35:12.410
No idea.

35:17.560 --> 35:19.528
- Month?
- August.

35:21.720 --> 35:23.484
You been sitting there
this whole time?

35:23.640 --> 35:25.608
Let's not get carried away.

35:29.760 --> 35:32.684
What'd the report say?
What's the news?

35:35.880 --> 35:37.769
We pulled 17 more cores.

35:39.680 --> 35:41.648
What?

35:41.760 --> 35:44.491
- No good?
- No good.

35:44.600 --> 35:45.965
Mm.

35:47.920 --> 35:49.649
More in the vicinity of great.

35:52.280 --> 35:54.408
Fuck you, Mike.
Don't mess with me, man.

35:56.840 --> 35:59.446
Eighth of an ounce per ton.

36:11.960 --> 36:13.849
Eighth... eighth of
an ounce per what?

36:13.960 --> 36:16.042
Eighth of an ounce per ton.

36:20.760 --> 36:22.762
What... what are you...
what are you saying, Mike?

36:22.880 --> 36:25.247
We got a strike in.

36:26.600 --> 36:27.965
We got a gold mine?

36:29.520 --> 36:31.727
- We got a gold mine?
- We got a gold mine.

36:36.680 --> 36:39.445
We got a gold mine, Mike!
We got a gold mine, Mike!

36:39.560 --> 36:41.881
- We got a gold mine.
- We got a goddamn gold mine!

36:42.000 --> 36:44.207
We got a gold mine!

36:44.320 --> 36:47.005
We got a goddamn gold mine!

36:47.120 --> 36:48.531
We got a goddamn...

36:48.680 --> 36:50.091
Gold mine!

36:50.200 --> 36:51.690
We got a gold mine!

36:51.800 --> 36:53.016
I knew it, I knew it,

36:53.040 --> 36:55.646
I knew it, I knew it, I knew it.

36:57.240 --> 37:00.642
We got a goddamn gold mine!

37:00.760 --> 37:02.250
Fuck you, mosquitoes!

37:04.040 --> 37:06.042
<i>That moment...</i>

37:06.200 --> 37:09.568
<i>there's no way I could possibly
describe the feeling.</i>

37:09.680 --> 37:11.569
<i>It's amazing
how a little gold dust</i>

37:11.680 --> 37:13.842
<i>can just change everything.</i>

37:14.000 --> 37:17.482
<i>Now, for better or worse,
the ride had begun,</i>

37:17.600 --> 37:19.568
<i>and what a goddamn ride.</i>

37:22.120 --> 37:23.246
Okay, Okay.

37:23.360 --> 37:24.521
Oh, thank God.

37:26.440 --> 37:28.761
- To the best goddamn team
in the business. -Fucking-A.

37:28.880 --> 37:30.041
You're a stand-up guy, Kenny.

37:30.160 --> 37:32.686
- Sharing the wealth.
- Crazy, huh?

37:32.800 --> 37:33.801
To the mother lode.

37:33.920 --> 37:35.604
The mother lode.

37:46.200 --> 37:47.770
All right, baby.
Do me a favor.

37:47.880 --> 37:49.325
Close your eyes, will ya?

37:49.440 --> 37:51.442
- All right.
- Cover them with your hands.

37:52.800 --> 37:54.484
- Keep 'em closed.
- Okay.

37:56.640 --> 37:58.961
- I got you. I got you.
I got you. -Oh. Okay.

38:01.040 --> 38:05.728
One, two, three.

38:11.000 --> 38:12.764
It's gonna be our place.

38:12.880 --> 38:15.565
Away from it all, above it all,
just like we always wanted.

38:15.680 --> 38:17.045
You like it?

38:17.160 --> 38:18.730
- Huh?
- Yes, of... Yes.

38:18.840 --> 38:22.765
Okay, look... the house...
right here, all right?

38:22.880 --> 38:25.531
The kitchen, facing there.
The great room over here.

38:25.640 --> 38:27.483
- Two fireplaces.
- No...

38:27.600 --> 38:28.681
Can we afford this?

38:28.800 --> 38:30.689
Almost, baby. Almost.
We're almost there.

38:30.800 --> 38:32.880
All right, look at this.
Couple bedrooms on that end.

38:32.960 --> 38:34.644
- Couple bedrooms on that end.
- Okay.

38:34.760 --> 38:36.683
Look at this playground
for the kids, huh?

38:36.800 --> 38:38.040
How many kids you want to have?

38:43.960 --> 38:45.371
<i>Kitchen has to stay over here.</i>

38:45.480 --> 38:46.970
We gotta put it over here

38:47.080 --> 38:48.400
- to get the morning light.
- Yes!

38:48.440 --> 38:49.896
And a second kitchen
over on this side.

38:49.920 --> 38:52.048
A third one across the creek.

38:52.160 --> 38:54.049
<i>A fourth one
up there with the elk.</i>

39:12.400 --> 39:14.528
- Kenny, Kenny.
- Mm?

39:14.640 --> 39:15.926
This is Walt Kealer.

39:16.080 --> 39:17.844
- He publishes
<i>Gold Digger</i> magazine. -Mm.

39:18.000 --> 39:20.002
We reach
half a million subscribers,

39:20.120 --> 39:21.531
and they'd all love to know

39:21.640 --> 39:23.400
what you got cooking
over there in Indonesia.

39:23.480 --> 39:25.403
If you have a minute,
I'll buy you a drink.

39:27.320 --> 39:29.322
He's all yours, Walt.

39:34.000 --> 39:35.331
Hell, I read
<i>Gold Digger</i> magazine.

39:35.440 --> 39:37.329
Come on over.

39:37.440 --> 39:39.456
They say you bring this in,
you'll get the Golden Pickaxe.

39:39.480 --> 39:41.296
- Aw, shut up.
- What do you say about that?

39:41.320 --> 39:44.529
I'd say you
probably just jinxed it.

39:44.640 --> 39:47.689
- How many ounces you guessing?
- Hmm.

39:47.800 --> 39:50.644
Millions, Walt.
Absolutely millions.

39:50.760 --> 39:51.966
Placer mining?

39:52.080 --> 39:54.606
No. Hard rock.
This is varsity ball.

39:54.720 --> 39:56.210
How's the infrastructure?

39:56.320 --> 39:57.924
Building it from the ground up.

40:01.680 --> 40:03.045
Any message you'd like to give

40:03.160 --> 40:05.401
to the readers
of <i>Gold Digger</i> magazine?

40:09.880 --> 40:14.169
The last card you turn over
is the only one that matters.

40:14.280 --> 40:17.090
- Kenny, it's good to see you.
- Good morning, Beverly.

40:17.200 --> 40:19.123
Clive, how are you?

40:19.240 --> 40:21.607
- There he is.
- Good to see you, sir.

40:21.720 --> 40:23.688
- It's good to see you, son.
- Mm-hmm.

40:23.800 --> 40:26.531
You know, your father and I,

40:26.640 --> 40:28.802
we started together
in this business.

40:28.920 --> 40:31.446
Hell, I mean,
he put me in the business.

40:31.560 --> 40:33.210
I don't have to tell you that.

40:33.320 --> 40:36.688
He always spoke very highly
of you, Clive.

40:36.800 --> 40:38.643
He's one of the best men
I ever knew.

40:39.720 --> 40:40.926
- Yeah.
- Now!

40:41.080 --> 40:43.128
You have gone
from four to 23 cents

40:43.240 --> 40:45.368
on your first assay results.

40:45.480 --> 40:48.450
And you pulled in two more
to confirm those findings?

40:48.560 --> 40:50.449
Three more.

40:50.560 --> 40:51.686
- Three more?
- Mm-hmm.

40:51.840 --> 40:53.080
Well, that's fantastic.

40:53.200 --> 40:56.124
Well, I would like to underwrite

40:56.240 --> 40:59.449
a private placement
of Washoe stock.

40:59.600 --> 41:01.090
And I believe that we can raise

41:01.200 --> 41:03.328
anywhere between
$8 million and $10 million.

41:03.480 --> 41:04.720
Well, capital is definitely

41:04.840 --> 41:06.569
at the top of our agenda
right now.

41:06.680 --> 41:08.091
Well, yes, it is.

41:08.200 --> 41:10.806
And a lot of people are going
to want to make this deal,

41:10.920 --> 41:12.285
but history is on our side.

41:12.400 --> 41:13.686
Mm-hmm.

41:13.800 --> 41:15.416
But I just wish you'd
brought this to me sooner.

41:15.440 --> 41:18.011
- I could have helped you
from the get-go. -Hey.

41:19.520 --> 41:21.727
- Well, here we are.
- Here we are.

41:21.840 --> 41:23.251
Lloyd...

41:23.360 --> 41:25.601
top that off for me, will you?

41:25.720 --> 41:29.930
Straight black
with a spicer chaser.

41:50.360 --> 41:52.328
Mr. Wells, uh, coffee.

41:52.440 --> 41:53.771
There we are, Lloyd.
